<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="chapter-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Coordinate Systems</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        A <term>coordinate system</term> enables us to uniquely identify any point's location in space via an ordered tuple of <term>coordinates</term>,
        which are signed distances from the <term>origin</term> measured parallel to <term>coordinate axes</term>.
    </p>

    <p>
        A point's location in space relative to the origin also can be identified by a <term>position vector</term>,
        which is a vector with tail fixed to the origin and tip attached to the point of interest.
        Furthermore, a position vector is not static: It traces out the path the point takes as it moves through space over time.
    </p>

    <p>
        You have learned in previous math courses how to use the Cartesian,
        cylindrical,
        and spherical coordinate systems to describe locations in <term>three-dimensional space</term> ("3-space").
        We will review relevant concepts below and then extend them.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <xi:include href="ch2-section-cartesian-coordinates.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="ch2-section-spherical-coordinates.ptx" />

</chapter>